1
00:00:01,320 --> 00:00:02,800
WOMAN: Did you see
that spaceship in the hangar?

2
00:00:03,160 --> 00:00:04,440
WOMAN: Yeah, we found
that on the lake bed.

3
00:00:04,520 --> 00:00:05,520
In here!

4
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:06,760
CLARA: Wait
are they saying something?

5
00:00:06,840 --> 00:00:09,840
"The dark. The sword.
The forsaken. The temple."”

6
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:13,360
DOCTOR: These words actually rewrite the
synaptic connections in your brain.

7
00:00:13,440 --> 00:00:14,560
They're coordinates.

8
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:17,320
Someone is deliberately
getting people killed.

9
00:00:17,480 --> 00:00:19,360
-(YELLING)
-They're turning them into transmitters.

10
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:20,920
(YELLS)

11
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:22,040
(GASPS)

12
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:23,200
I can save you.

13
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:24,280
A new ghost.

14
00:00:24,360 --> 00:00:25,400
CLARA: Oh, no, no, no, no.

15
00:00:27,920 --> 00:00:30,240
So there's this man,
he has a time machine.

16
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:33,880
Up and down history he goes,
zip, zip, zip, zip, zip.

17
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:35,360
Getting into scrapes.

18
00:00:36,360 --> 00:00:38,080
Another thing he has

19
00:00:38,160 --> 00:00:43,920
is a passion for the works
of Ludwig van Beethoven.

20
00:00:44,200 --> 00:00:47,080
And one day he thinks, "What's the point
of having a time machine

21
00:00:47,160 --> 00:00:49,200
"if you don't get to meet your heroes?"

22
00:00:49,320 --> 00:00:52,760
So, off he goes to
18th-century Germany.

23
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:55,120
But he can't find Beethoven anywhere.

24
00:00:55,200 --> 00:00:56,600
No one's heard of him.

25
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:59,440
Not even his family have any idea

26
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:01,920
who the time traveller
is talking about.

27
00:01:03,360 --> 00:01:06,360
Beethoven literally doesn't exist.

28
00:01:09,880 --> 00:01:11,200
This didn't happen, by the way.

29
00:01:13,160 --> 00:01:16,120
I've met Beethoven. Nice chap.

30
00:01:17,240 --> 00:01:19,360
Very intense. Loved an arm wrestle.

31
00:01:19,520 --> 00:01:24,360
No, this is called
the Bootstrap Paradox.

32
00:01:25,120 --> 00:01:26,240
Google it.

33
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:28,840
The time traveller panics.

34
00:01:29,800 --> 00:01:32,960
He can't bear the thought of a world
without the music of Beethoven.

35
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:37,760
Luckily, he brought all of his Beethoven
sheet music for Ludwig to sign.

36
00:01:38,360 --> 00:01:42,680
So he copies out
all the concertos and the symphonies

37
00:01:43,480 --> 00:01:45,840
and he gets them published.

38
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:48,600
He becomes Beethoven.

39
00:01:49,360 --> 00:01:52,920
And history continues
with barely a feather ruffled.

40
00:01:57,320 --> 00:01:58,440
(AMPLIFIER DISTORTION)

41
00:01:58,520 --> 00:02:00,880
My question is this.

42
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:05,720
Who put those notes
and phrases together?

43
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:08,760
Who really composed Beethoven's Fifth?

44
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:13,320
(PLAYING BEETHOVEN'S SYMPHONY NO. 5)

45
00:02:17,120 --> 00:02:19,040
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

46
00:02:55,880 --> 00:02:57,120
DOCTOR: Where's Bennett?
We need to get going.

47
00:02:57,200 --> 00:02:58,720
O'DONNELL: Oh, he's still throwing up.

48
00:02:58,800 --> 00:03:01,280
One small step for man,
one giant... (WRETCHES)

49
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:03,360
Time travel does that sometimes.

50
00:03:03,440 --> 00:03:05,040
I somehow doubt that
Rose, or Martha or Amy

51
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,120
lost their breakfast on the first trip.

52
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:09,880
You seem to know an awful lot about me.

53
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:12,840
I used to be military intelligence.

54
00:03:13,040 --> 00:03:16,400
I was demoted for dangling
a colleague out a window.

55
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:17,800
In anger?

56
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:20,560
Is there another way to dangle
someone out the window?

57
00:03:22,800 --> 00:03:24,000
What year are we in?

58
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:29,240
1980.

59
00:03:29,640 --> 00:03:33,520
(SCOFFS) So, pre-Harold Saxon,
pre-the Minister of War,

60
00:03:33,600 --> 00:03:35,520
pre-the moon exploding,
the big bat coming out...

61
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:36,880
The Minister of War?

62
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:39,040
-Yeah?
-No, never mind.

63
00:03:39,160 --> 00:03:41,000
I expect I'll find out soon enough.

64
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:45,280
Sorry about that.
The prawn sandwich might have been off.

65
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:46,480
Uh-huh.

66
00:03:47,120 --> 00:03:48,480
Uh, don't worry.

67
00:03:50,200 --> 00:03:51,200
Shall we go?

68
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:54,200
Uh, just one sec.
I've just got something in my boot.

69
00:03:58,040 --> 00:04:00,200
It's bigger on the inside,
it's bigger on the inside,

70
00:04:00,280 --> 00:04:01,920
it's bigger on the inside!

71
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:04,680
(LAUGHS) How can it be
bigger on the inside, Bennett?

72
00:04:05,320 --> 00:04:06,480
(CLEARS THROAT)

73
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:08,760
Okay, let's roll.

74
00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:13,840
BENNETT:
Why have we gone to Russia?

75
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:14,920
DOCTOR: Uh, we haven't.

76
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,840
We're still in Scotland.
This is the town before it flooded.

77
00:04:18,240 --> 00:04:21,080
The TARDIS has brought us to when
the spaceship first touched down.

78
00:04:21,400 --> 00:04:23,360
But here and now
it's the height of the Cold War.

79
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:26,760
The military were being trained
for offensives on Soviet soil.

80
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:46,840
Oh, is that the pilot?

81
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:50,680
My God, look at the size of it.

82
00:04:51,640 --> 00:04:53,840
DOCTOR: No, that's the body.

83
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,320
O'DONNELL:
What do you mean, "the body"?

84
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:57,280
This isn't just any spaceship.

85
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:00,400
It's a hearse.

86
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:02,280
The suspended animation
chamber is still here,

87
00:05:02,360 --> 00:05:03,960
and the power cells for the engine.

88
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:06,880
And there are no markings on the wall.

89
00:05:08,840 --> 00:05:10,000
Yet.

90
00:05:10,920 --> 00:05:12,040
Greetings!

91
00:05:12,600 --> 00:05:14,400
It's him. That's the ghost
from the Drum.

92
00:05:16,280 --> 00:05:17,600
(SNIFFING)

93
00:05:17,680 --> 00:05:19,800
Remarkable. (GASPS)

94
00:05:21,320 --> 00:05:22,920
And humans, too.

95
00:05:23,640 --> 00:05:26,600
Albar Prentis, Funeral Director.

96
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:28,040
You're from Tivoli, aren't you?

97
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:30,840
(PROUDLY) The most invaded
planet in the galaxy.

98
00:05:31,160 --> 00:05:33,200
Our capital city has a sign saying,

99
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:36,520
"If you occupied us,
you'd be home by now."

100
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:39,200
Yes, I've had dealings with your lot
before, I can't say I'm a fan.

101
00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:42,240
Oh, we do tend to antagonize. (LAUGHS)

102
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:43,560
DOCTOR:
What are you doing here?

103
00:05:43,640 --> 00:05:44,720
Ah, yes. Of course.

104
00:05:45,400 --> 00:05:49,560
This is the Fisher King.

105
00:05:50,040 --> 00:05:54,320
He and his armies invaded Tivoli
and enslaved us for ten glorious years.

106
00:05:55,080 --> 00:05:57,760
(DISGUSTED) Until we were
liberated by the Arcateenians.

107
00:05:58,040 --> 00:06:01,600
But, thank the gods,
soon we'd irritated them so much,

108
00:06:01,680 --> 00:06:03,240
they enslaved us, too. (LAUGHS)

109
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:06,680
My first proper alien,
and he's an idiot.

110
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:09,840
And now, in accordance with
Arcateenian custom,

111
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:14,760
I've come to bury him
on a barren, savage outpost.

112
00:06:15,160 --> 00:06:16,360
You mean the town?

113
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:17,640
He means the planet.

114
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:22,400
Although, at the risk of starting
a bidding war, you could enslave me.

115
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:24,480
In the ship,
I have directions to my planet

116
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:27,800
and a selection of items
that you can appraise me with.

117
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:28,960
Listen, we've come from the future,

118
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:30,680
you're about to send
some sort of a signal.

119
00:06:30,760 --> 00:06:32,880
How do you do it? Is it a special pen?

120
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:35,880
-What are you talking about?
-The technology you use.

121
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:39,640
The thing that wrenches the soul
out of the body and makes it repeat

122
00:06:39,720 --> 00:06:41,200
your coordinates for eternity.

123
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:43,160
Give it to me now,
I'm going to take the batteries out.

124
00:06:43,240 --> 00:06:45,600
We don't have anything
like that. (LAUGHS)

125
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:48,120
Even this belongs to
the glorious Arcateenians.

126
00:06:48,760 --> 00:06:50,280
So who sends the message?

127
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:52,520
(SNIFFING)

128
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:57,000
DOCTOR: Back to the TARDIS.
I need to talk to Clara.

129
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:19,640
You've been here before.

130
00:07:20,360 --> 00:07:22,000
In situations like this before.

131
00:07:22,840 --> 00:07:25,120
Yeah, not exactly like, but...

132
00:07:25,880 --> 00:07:27,280
Yeah, once or twice.

133
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:29,160
So you've had to deal with
people who are scared.

134
00:07:29,960 --> 00:07:31,160
What do you say to them?

135
00:07:31,960 --> 00:07:34,000
I'm asking what I should say to you.

136
00:07:35,240 --> 00:07:36,920
That it will be all right.

137
00:07:37,480 --> 00:07:38,840
That the Doctor will save us.

138
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:41,280
And when you say it, do you believe it?

139
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:45,560
Yeah. Yeah, I do.

140
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:47,480
And now?

141
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:54,080
Cass thinks the Doctor's saying
something different to the others.

142
00:07:54,720 --> 00:08:00,200
He's saying, "Moran,
Pritchard, apprentice..."

143
00:08:00,280 --> 00:08:02,160
No... "Prentis"?

144
00:08:03,480 --> 00:08:09,240
“"...O'Donnell, Clara,
Doctor, Bennett, Cass.”™

145
00:08:10,360 --> 00:08:11,800
It's just a list of all our names.

146
00:08:12,560 --> 00:08:14,960
And when he finishes, he just goes
back to the beginning again,

147
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:16,120
over and over, that's it.

148
00:08:16,200 --> 00:08:17,280
Who's Prentis?

149
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:19,400
(MOBILE PHONE RINGS)

150
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:21,960
-It's the Doctor.
-He's alive?

151
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:24,000
For the moment.

152
00:08:25,320 --> 00:08:28,200
CLARA: Doctor?
Doctor, are you all right?

153
00:08:28,680 --> 00:08:32,200
Yeah, fine. So listen,
the spaceship, it's a hearse.

154
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:34,600
Clara, what's wrong?

155
00:08:35,960 --> 00:08:37,280
Another ghost has appeared.

156
00:08:37,400 --> 00:08:39,800
What? Who? Has someone died?

157
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:42,840
Doctor, it's you.

158
00:08:47,960 --> 00:08:49,040
You okay?

159
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:50,160
Yeah.

160
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:52,200
Well, currently.

161
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:54,000
What does it mean?

162
00:08:55,880 --> 00:08:56,960
It means I die.

163
00:08:57,160 --> 00:08:59,680
No, not necessarily, we can change
the sequence of events, so...

164
00:09:00,080 --> 00:09:02,000
This isn't the potential future.

165
00:09:02,840 --> 00:09:04,080
This is the future now.

166
00:09:04,840 --> 00:09:06,440
It's already happened.

167
00:09:06,760 --> 00:09:08,520
The proof is right there
in front of you.

168
00:09:16,960 --> 00:09:17,960
I have to die.

169
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:20,960
No.

170
00:09:21,120 --> 00:09:22,520
You can change things.

171
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:23,720
I can't.

172
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:27,840
Even the tiniest change,
the ramifications could be catastrophic,

173
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:30,520
could spread carnage
and chaos across the universe,

174
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:32,440
like ripples on a pond.

175
00:09:33,760 --> 00:09:36,280
Oh, well, I've had a good innings.

176
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:38,800
This regeneration,
it's a bit of a clerical error, anyway.

177
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:41,000
Gotta go sometime.

178
00:09:41,080 --> 00:09:42,360
Not with me!

179
00:09:42,720 --> 00:09:45,280
Die with whoever comes after me,
you do not leave me!

180
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:49,160
Clara, I need to talk to you
just on your own.

181
00:09:53,640 --> 00:09:54,720
Listen to me.

182
00:09:55,040 --> 00:09:59,440
We all have to face death eventually,
be it ours or someone else's.

183
00:10:01,320 --> 00:10:02,440
I'm not ready yet.

184
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:06,240
I don't want to think
about that, not yet.

185
00:10:06,560 --> 00:10:10,160
I can't change what's already happened.
There are rules.

186
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:11,520
So break them.

187
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:14,760
And anyway, you owe me.

188
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:20,840
You've made yourself essential to me,
you've given me something else to be.

189
00:10:21,280 --> 00:10:23,880
And you can't do that and then die,
it's not fair.

190
00:10:23,960 --> 00:10:24,960
Clara...

191
00:10:25,040 --> 00:10:28,320
No, Doctor, I don't care about your
rules or your bloody survivor's guilt,

192
00:10:28,400 --> 00:10:32,840
if you love me in any way,
you'll come back.

193
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:40,760
Doctor, are you...

194
00:10:43,080 --> 00:10:45,080
I can't save Moran or Pritchard.

195
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:47,080
I know. Like you said, if you can,

196
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:48,800
if you can find out
why this is happening,

197
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:50,840
then maybe you can stop them
killing anybody else.

198
00:10:50,920 --> 00:10:52,320
You can save us.

199
00:10:54,560 --> 00:10:56,280
And you can stop it happening to you.

200
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:59,760
I'll do what I can,
but the future has already happened.

201
00:11:00,360 --> 00:11:02,720
We've just met the undertaker
and he's still alive.

202
00:11:09,440 --> 00:11:10,920
(GASPS)

203
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:18,920
(SNIFFING)

204
00:11:23,560 --> 00:11:25,240
(GROWLING)

205
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:29,200
(LASER SHOTS FIRING)

206
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:32,640
(PHONE CLICKS IN RECEIVER)

207
00:11:32,720 --> 00:11:35,840
So, ghost me.
You've got a better view than me.

208
00:11:36,600 --> 00:11:37,760
DOCTOR: How do I look?

209
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:40,080
Any signs of trauma, any scars?

210
00:11:40,160 --> 00:11:42,680
-Any clues as to how I die?
-No.

211
00:11:42,760 --> 00:11:44,800
Nothing. You're the same
as all the other ghosts,

212
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:46,120
with the weird black eyes and...

213
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:52,480
No, no, wait.

214
00:11:53,800 --> 00:11:56,480
Your coat is torn on the right shoulder.

215
00:11:58,280 --> 00:12:00,680
I assume that I'm just saying
the same thing as the others.

216
00:12:00,880 --> 00:12:05,480
No, you're saying a list of names,
our names mainly.

217
00:12:05,560 --> 00:12:09,640
Moran, Pritchard, Prentis,
O'Donnell, Clara, Doctor, Bennett, Cass.

218
00:12:09,760 --> 00:12:12,080
-Who's Prentis?
-DOCTOR: Mole-faced chap.

219
00:12:12,720 --> 00:12:13,720
(WHOOSHING)

220
00:12:14,560 --> 00:12:15,720
-(STATIC)
-What's the matter?

221
00:12:15,800 --> 00:12:17,320
Clara, what's happening?

222
00:12:18,760 --> 00:12:19,760
(INAUDIBLE)

223
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:21,520
You've moved inside.
You're inside here now.

224
00:12:21,600 --> 00:12:23,960
-What am I doing?
-Uh...

225
00:12:24,040 --> 00:12:25,200
(INAUDIBLE)

226
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:27,920
Nothing. You're just standing there.

227
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:30,440
I'm not trying to kill you?
Why am I not trying to kill you?

228
00:12:33,320 --> 00:12:34,360
No, wait. You're moving,

229
00:12:36,120 --> 00:12:37,600
going toward the control panel.

230
00:12:39,440 --> 00:12:41,000
(BEEPING)

231
00:12:45,680 --> 00:12:46,680
Oh, no!

232
00:12:47,400 --> 00:12:49,680
He's opened the Faraday cage.
He's let the other ghosts out.

233
00:12:49,760 --> 00:12:51,360
Clara, I need to talk to me now.

234
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:53,200
What, didn't you hear me?
You just opened the Faraday cage.

235
00:12:53,280 --> 00:12:54,840
The other ghosts are outside.
Shouldn't we be hiding?

236
00:12:54,920 --> 00:12:57,320
In a minute.
I need to talk to the ghost me.

237
00:13:01,200 --> 00:13:02,240
Okay.

238
00:13:02,360 --> 00:13:03,360
CLARA: Doctor, you're on.

239
00:13:05,520 --> 00:13:10,000
Doctor, such an honour.
I've always been a huge admirer.

240
00:13:10,080 --> 00:13:13,600
This is really a delight.
Finally, someone worth talking to.

241
00:13:13,720 --> 00:13:16,400
So, firstly, why are you here?

242
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:19,520
Clara, Clara, what's happening?

243
00:13:20,040 --> 00:13:21,160
Um...

244
00:13:23,400 --> 00:13:24,440
Uh...

245
00:13:25,320 --> 00:13:26,880
You've just stopped.

246
00:13:28,480 --> 00:13:29,560
CLARA: Oh, no, wait.
You've started again.

247
00:13:29,640 --> 00:13:30,800
(INAUDIBLE)

248
00:13:32,120 --> 00:13:33,400
His message changed.

249
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:35,520
He's saying something different.
He's saying...

250
00:13:36,200 --> 00:13:37,640
-What?
-What?

251
00:13:37,760 --> 00:13:38,920
What?

252
00:13:40,960 --> 00:13:43,760
He's saying,
"The chamber will open tonight.”

253
00:13:45,880 --> 00:13:48,560
Clara, now the ghosts are out,
go to the Faraday cage.

254
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:50,480
They won't be able to get you in there.

255
00:13:50,560 --> 00:13:52,880
-Oh, there's a problem.
-CLARA: Problem!

256
00:13:53,120 --> 00:13:55,640
What problem? Oh, really, 'cause
everything else is going so smoothly.

257
00:13:55,840 --> 00:13:57,600
The phone signal won't be able
to get through.

258
00:13:57,720 --> 00:13:58,720
What you'll have to do...

259
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:00,520
I know, put the phone outside

260
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:02,720
and you can watch it through
the little round porthole.

261
00:14:02,880 --> 00:14:05,840
And when you see it ringing, if it is
safe to do so, go out and answer it.

262
00:14:06,120 --> 00:14:07,160
Okay, well, how long are you gonna...

263
00:14:07,240 --> 00:14:08,520
Clara, listen to me,

264
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:10,280
don't let that phone out of your sight.

265
00:14:10,680 --> 00:14:12,080
I need to be able to reach you.

266
00:14:12,600 --> 00:14:14,520
I need to know everything my ghost does.

267
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:15,680
Do you understand?

268
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:18,880
I'll come back for you. I swear.

269
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:21,360
(STATIC)

270
00:14:27,160 --> 00:14:28,840
Come on.

271
00:14:29,080 --> 00:14:30,080
Oh, wait a minute.

272
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:31,440
-Not you, O'Donnell.
-Well, why not?

273
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:33,080
Someone need to stay here
and mind the shop.

274
00:14:33,160 --> 00:14:36,000
-(SCOFFS)
-What if Clara calls?

275
00:14:36,160 --> 00:14:40,360
The last bloke that said something like
that to me got dangled out of a window.

276
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:44,320
Maybe the Doctor's right.
Maybe it's best if you stay here.

277
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:47,640
Never going to happen.
Seriously, have you two met me?

278
00:14:59,960 --> 00:15:01,120
Prentis.

279
00:15:03,120 --> 00:15:04,120
Prentis!

280
00:15:08,960 --> 00:15:11,080
Guess that dead body
wasn't so dead after all.

281
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:13,080
And now we've got the writing.

282
00:15:14,680 --> 00:15:16,720
DOCTOR: The Fisher King
did it himself.

283
00:15:19,640 --> 00:15:21,280
The future is still coming.

284
00:15:28,680 --> 00:15:30,800
He's taking the suspended-animation
chamber to the judge.

285
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:35,480
(ROARING)

286
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:37,600
What was that?

287
00:15:37,720 --> 00:15:39,400
We need to get back to the TARDIS.

288
00:15:39,640 --> 00:15:40,720
Now!

289
00:15:43,160 --> 00:15:45,080
(ROARING)

290
00:15:47,600 --> 00:15:48,600
Let's cut it off!

291
00:15:51,160 --> 00:15:52,160
(ROARING)

292
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:54,040
O'DONNELL: Let's split up!

293
00:15:55,680 --> 00:15:57,480
Go on, Bennett!

294
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:11,120
(CRASHING FOOTSTEPS)

295
00:16:11,320 --> 00:16:13,000
(GROWLING)

296
00:16:14,280 --> 00:16:15,920
(PANTING)

297
00:16:19,120 --> 00:16:21,040
(GROWLING INTENSIFIES)

298
00:16:35,960 --> 00:16:37,560
(PANTING)

299
00:16:53,120 --> 00:16:56,840
(ROARING)

300
00:16:57,080 --> 00:16:58,080
(LASER SHOT FIRING)

301
00:17:00,120 --> 00:17:01,280
No, Bennett, wait!

302
00:17:02,200 --> 00:17:04,280
(DISTANT MOANING)

303
00:17:14,680 --> 00:17:16,400
-(GASPS)
-Why did you come?

304
00:17:16,480 --> 00:17:18,280
You shouldn't have come.
I mean, you never listen to anyone.

305
00:17:18,360 --> 00:17:20,440
-It drives me mad.
-To keep an eye on you.

306
00:17:21,680 --> 00:17:22,760
Idiot.

307
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:27,800
So, don't die.

308
00:17:42,440 --> 00:17:44,120
Who's next on the list?

309
00:17:55,360 --> 00:17:57,400
BENNETT: That list your ghost
was saying,

310
00:17:57,560 --> 00:18:00,040
that's the order in which
people are going to die. Isn't it?

311
00:18:00,160 --> 00:18:01,720
I mean, I've only just figured that out,

312
00:18:01,960 --> 00:18:03,640
but you knew that all along.

313
00:18:03,720 --> 00:18:04,760
Didn't you?

314
00:18:05,120 --> 00:18:09,720
Moran, Pritchard, Prentis, O'Donnell.

315
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,560
I thought, perhaps
because her ghost wasn't there

316
00:18:12,880 --> 00:18:15,000
in the future, like Prentis' was...

317
00:18:16,400 --> 00:18:17,880
I thought maybe...

318
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:21,560
Maybe it wouldn't happen.
Maybe she stood a chance.

319
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:23,960
Yeah, but you didn't try very hard
to stop her, though, did you?

320
00:18:26,480 --> 00:18:28,760
It's almost like you
wanted to test your theory.

321
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:30,440
So, who's next?

322
00:18:32,160 --> 00:18:33,840
-Clara.
-Yeah.

323
00:18:35,800 --> 00:18:37,840
Except now you're gonna
do something about it, aren't you?

324
00:18:38,520 --> 00:18:40,360
Yeah, 'cause it's getting closer to you.

325
00:18:40,480 --> 00:18:41,480
You change history

326
00:18:41,880 --> 00:18:44,440
to save yourself,
but not to save O'Donnell.

327
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:47,320
You wouldn't save her.

328
00:18:47,800 --> 00:18:50,720
This isn't about saving me.
I'm a dead man walking.

329
00:18:53,160 --> 00:18:54,720
I'm changing history to save Clara.

330
00:19:11,160 --> 00:19:12,840
(GASPS)

331
00:19:19,040 --> 00:19:20,440
O'Donnell's dead.

332
00:19:34,920 --> 00:19:36,520
Oh, no. No, no, no.

333
00:19:37,080 --> 00:19:38,680
Oh, now, don't you dare.
Don't you dare!

334
00:19:50,360 --> 00:19:52,320
.—(TYPING)
-Big day for you.

335
00:19:52,840 --> 00:19:55,680
Time travel, twice.

336
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:57,720
Whoa, uh, really?

337
00:19:58,200 --> 00:19:59,480
When are we going to?

338
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:01,560
DOCTOR: Off the map,
out of the rule book.

339
00:20:02,280 --> 00:20:03,680
What if I don't die?

340
00:20:04,360 --> 00:20:05,360
What if I refuse?

341
00:20:06,120 --> 00:20:08,400
I'm gonna go back to the base
and I'm gonna save Clara

342
00:20:08,480 --> 00:20:09,840
because that's what I do.

343
00:20:09,920 --> 00:20:12,520
And I don't see anyone here
who's going to stop me.

344
00:20:12,600 --> 00:20:16,200
(DISTORTED WHOOSHING)

345
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:30,200
Why're we still here?

346
00:20:32,800 --> 00:20:35,400
No! No, no, no, no.

347
00:20:37,720 --> 00:20:40,280
-What?
-We've moved half an hour backwards.

348
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:42,400
I'm locked in my own time stream.

349
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:45,080
The TARDIS won't let me leave.

350
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:46,880
Well, what do we do?

351
00:20:46,960 --> 00:20:50,520
Now we have to keep out of sight,
until time catches up.

352
00:20:51,400 --> 00:20:52,880
DOCTOR: Where's Bennett?
We need to get going.

353
00:20:52,960 --> 00:20:53,960
O'DONNELL: Probably still throwing up.

354
00:20:57,400 --> 00:21:00,600
Prentis. He's alive.

355
00:21:01,640 --> 00:21:03,960
No, he's just not dead yet
and we don't tell him.

356
00:21:04,040 --> 00:21:05,840
-But he's right there. We can just...
-No.

357
00:21:06,040 --> 00:21:09,240
However that sentence ends,
no, we can't.

358
00:21:10,320 --> 00:21:12,280
Save him and you want to save O'Donnell.

359
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:14,640
You can't cheat time. I just tried.

360
00:21:15,400 --> 00:21:18,640
You can't just go back
and cut off tragedy at the root.

361
00:21:19,760 --> 00:21:22,800
Because you find yourself talking to
someone you just saw dead on a slab.

362
00:21:24,440 --> 00:21:26,360
Because then you really do see ghosts.

363
00:21:28,760 --> 00:21:30,320
We don't tell him. Understand?

364
00:21:30,400 --> 00:21:33,080
Not a word. We don't have that right.

365
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:43,400
PRENTIS: Albar Prentis,
Funeral Director.

366
00:21:43,520 --> 00:21:44,520
BENNETT: You're from Tivoli, aren't you?

367
00:21:44,600 --> 00:21:46,960
The most invaded planet in the galaxy.

368
00:21:47,440 --> 00:21:49,360
PRENTIS: Our capital city
has a sign saying,

369
00:21:49,640 --> 00:21:52,640
"If you occupied us,
you'd be home by now."

370
00:21:52,760 --> 00:21:55,480
DOCTOR: Yes, I've had dealings with
your lot before, I can't say I'm a fan.

371
00:21:55,560 --> 00:21:59,000
PRENTIS: Oh, we do tend
to antagonize. (LAUGHS)

372
00:21:59,320 --> 00:22:00,360
(THUD)

373
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:03,640
-DOCTOR: What are you doing here?
-Ah, yes, of course.

374
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:10,200
The Doc, the sword,
the forsaken, the temple.

375
00:22:17,160 --> 00:22:18,480
When we found out
what the ghost was saying,

376
00:22:18,560 --> 00:22:20,080
we weren't surprised,

377
00:22:20,160 --> 00:22:21,880
because the words,

378
00:22:21,960 --> 00:22:24,520
they were already inside us.

379
00:22:25,800 --> 00:22:27,880
But you...

380
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:29,200
You were, weren't you?

381
00:22:29,400 --> 00:22:31,000
You didn't know what
the words were going to be.

382
00:22:31,360 --> 00:22:34,360
Uh, no, I didn't. How did you know?

383
00:22:35,160 --> 00:22:37,400
Who was the one person who didn't
see the writing in the space ship?

384
00:22:38,680 --> 00:22:40,680
Me. Cass wouldn't let me go inside.

385
00:22:40,760 --> 00:22:42,800
That's why the ghosts didn't
hurt you when they had the chance,

386
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:44,440
because the message isn't inside you.

387
00:22:45,600 --> 00:22:47,880
Yes, I suppose that makes sense.

388
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:49,480
So you can get the phone back?

389
00:22:50,640 --> 00:22:51,680
What?

390
00:22:55,360 --> 00:22:57,400
She's saying I should
go get the phone back.

391
00:22:58,040 --> 00:23:01,240
-No.
-Listen. Listen, I need...

392
00:23:03,480 --> 00:23:05,600
We... We need to be able
to contact the Doctor

393
00:23:05,680 --> 00:23:07,000
and you are the only one
who can do this.

394
00:23:10,280 --> 00:23:11,280
Okay.

395
00:23:15,800 --> 00:23:17,280
No. She's right.

396
00:23:17,720 --> 00:23:19,560
Neither of you can get it back.

397
00:23:32,480 --> 00:23:33,520
What? What is it?

398
00:23:33,600 --> 00:23:34,640
-What does she say?
-LUNN: It doesn't matter.

399
00:23:36,560 --> 00:23:37,560
Please.

400
00:23:37,680 --> 00:23:40,760
She said to ask you whether
travelling with the Doctor changed you

401
00:23:41,840 --> 00:23:44,360
and why you always have to put
other people's lives at risk.

402
00:23:48,040 --> 00:23:49,640
He taught me to do what has to be done.

403
00:23:52,240 --> 00:23:55,000
(STRUGGLING) We should get going.

404
00:24:05,440 --> 00:24:06,520
I need more time.

405
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:09,560
It's too soon. I haven't saved her yet.

406
00:24:10,400 --> 00:24:14,920
Tick-tock, tick-tock, tick-tock,
tick-tock, tick-tock.

407
00:24:15,080 --> 00:24:17,480
I've got no choice now.
I have to face the Fisher King.

408
00:24:17,560 --> 00:24:18,840
You, back to the TARDIS.

409
00:24:29,520 --> 00:24:32,200
Look, he'll be fine.

410
00:24:32,400 --> 00:24:33,920
I promise.

411
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:40,520
Okay. Didn't need anyone
to translate that.

412
00:24:46,960 --> 00:24:48,000
(DOOR CLICKS SHUT)

413
00:24:54,080 --> 00:24:55,520
Now I'm ready.

414
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:38,040
I've come from the future.

415
00:25:38,800 --> 00:25:39,800
(LOW GROWLING)

416
00:25:39,880 --> 00:25:41,800
I've seen the chaos you caused,
the bloodshed.

417
00:25:42,960 --> 00:25:46,320
FISHER KING:
Tell me what you have seen.

418
00:25:47,120 --> 00:25:49,360
-Ghosts.
-Ghosts?

419
00:25:49,960 --> 00:25:52,080
Souls wrenched from the dead,

420
00:25:52,480 --> 00:25:55,480
repeating directions to here,
to this spot, over and over.

421
00:25:55,760 --> 00:25:59,560
FISHER KING: How many ghosts
do I create? How many?

422
00:25:59,640 --> 00:26:02,280
Four that I know of.
Maybe five, by now.

423
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:03,800
Probably more since I left.

424
00:26:03,920 --> 00:26:06,800
FISHER KING: My ghosts
will make more ghosts.

425
00:26:08,160 --> 00:26:11,040
FISHER KING:
Enough to bring an armada,

426
00:26:12,280 --> 00:26:17,200
enough to wake me from my sleep.

427
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:20,120
(WHIRRING)

428
00:26:21,480 --> 00:26:23,120
(BEEPING)

429
00:26:50,200 --> 00:26:51,480
(INHALES DEEPLY)

430
00:27:27,280 --> 00:27:28,600
(RHYTHMIC BANGING)

431
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:32,400
What will happen
when your people arrive?

432
00:27:32,720 --> 00:27:37,440
FISHER KING: We will drain the
oceans and put the humans in chains.

433
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:40,600
DOCTOR: This world is protected, by me.

434
00:27:41,240 --> 00:27:42,760
FISHER KING: Yes,

435
00:27:42,840 --> 00:27:47,200
one man, lost in time.

436
00:28:05,520 --> 00:28:07,960
COMPUTER VOICE:
Door emergency security lock.

437
00:28:14,720 --> 00:28:15,720
(RHYTHMIC BANGING)

438
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:18,360
FISHER KING: The seed
of their destruction is already sown.

439
00:28:19,120 --> 00:28:22,520
They will die. The message will be sent.

440
00:28:23,120 --> 00:28:25,360
My people will come

441
00:28:25,760 --> 00:28:31,000
and you will do nothing to stop it,

442
00:28:32,320 --> 00:28:34,080
Time Lord.

443
00:28:38,320 --> 00:28:39,560
Hey! No, no, no, no!

444
00:28:39,640 --> 00:28:41,280
Cass, wait!

445
00:28:41,840 --> 00:28:42,880
What are you doing?

446
00:28:45,520 --> 00:28:47,360
Look... Lunn, he is going to be fine.
I promise.

447
00:28:47,440 --> 00:28:48,680
We have to stay here.

448
00:28:50,520 --> 00:28:53,040
I know that look. I do that look.

449
00:28:56,640 --> 00:28:58,160
Okay, fine.

450
00:28:58,240 --> 00:28:59,760
But we stick together.

451
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:13,920
Time Lords,

452
00:29:14,080 --> 00:29:16,760
cowardly, vain curators,

453
00:29:16,840 --> 00:29:18,800
who suddenly remembered they had teeth,

454
00:29:18,880 --> 00:29:21,880
and became the most
war-like race in the galaxy.

455
00:29:22,240 --> 00:29:23,840
But, you...

456
00:29:24,120 --> 00:29:25,840
You!

457
00:29:26,120 --> 00:29:29,120
You are curious.

458
00:29:29,440 --> 00:29:30,840
You have seen the words, too.

459
00:29:30,920 --> 00:29:33,880
I can hear them tick inside you.

460
00:29:34,280 --> 00:29:37,640
But you are still locked
in your history,

461
00:29:37,760 --> 00:29:41,160
still slavishly protecting time.

462
00:29:41,400 --> 00:29:42,880
Willing to die,

463
00:29:42,960 --> 00:29:45,560
rather than change a word of the future.

464
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:48,880
(WHISPERING) Lunn?

465
00:29:58,040 --> 00:29:59,080
Lunn?

466
00:30:04,960 --> 00:30:06,080
Lunn?

467
00:30:23,240 --> 00:30:24,480
Oh, Cass.

468
00:30:26,280 --> 00:30:27,840
Cass?

469
00:30:28,840 --> 00:30:29,920
Cass?

470
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:35,480
Ugh. Idiot. I'm an idiot.

471
00:30:50,280 --> 00:30:52,440
(METAL SCRAPING)

472
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:13,960
(SCRAPING CONTINUES)

473
00:31:18,320 --> 00:31:21,080
You will be a strong beacon.

474
00:31:21,320 --> 00:31:24,120
How many ghosts can I make of you?

475
00:31:24,320 --> 00:31:26,600
You really have got
a lot in common with the Tivolians.

476
00:31:27,720 --> 00:31:29,120
You'll both do anything to survive.

477
00:31:29,240 --> 00:31:30,760
DOCTOR: They'll surrender to anyone.

478
00:31:31,040 --> 00:31:34,400
You will hijack other peoples' souls

479
00:31:34,600 --> 00:31:37,320
and turn them into
electromagnetic projections.

480
00:31:38,520 --> 00:31:40,320
That will to endure,

481
00:31:42,560 --> 00:31:43,880
that refusal

482
00:31:45,040 --> 00:31:47,080
to ever cease,

483
00:31:48,320 --> 00:31:49,480
it's extraordinary.

484
00:31:49,760 --> 00:31:52,960
And it makes a fellow think,
because you know what,

485
00:31:53,520 --> 00:31:57,600
if all I had to do to survive is tweak
The future a bit, what's stopping me?

486
00:31:57,720 --> 00:32:00,920
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, the ripple effect.
Maybe it will mean

487
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:05,160
that the universe will be ruled by cats
or something in the future.

488
00:32:05,320 --> 00:32:06,480
But the way I see it,

489
00:32:06,560 --> 00:32:10,480
even a ghastly future
is better than no future at all.

490
00:32:12,720 --> 00:32:14,920
You robbed those people of their deaths.

491
00:32:16,120 --> 00:32:18,440
Made them nothing more
than a message in a bottle.

492
00:32:19,200 --> 00:32:22,400
You violated something
more important than time.

493
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:27,960
DOCTOR: You bent
the rules of life and death.

494
00:32:28,960 --> 00:32:32,200
So I'm putting things straight.

495
00:32:33,600 --> 00:32:35,440
Here. Now.

496
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:38,120
This is where your story ends.

497
00:32:39,240 --> 00:32:41,280
(GROWLING)

498
00:32:43,800 --> 00:32:45,560
(WHIRRING)

499
00:32:58,920 --> 00:33:01,640
(METAL SCRAPING)

500
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:11,000
(INAUDIBLE)

501
00:33:23,360 --> 00:33:25,360
(LOW VIBRATING)

502
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:37,400
(CASS GASPS)

503
00:33:39,160 --> 00:33:40,560
Oh! There you are.

504
00:33:40,960 --> 00:33:43,680
There is nothing you can do.

505
00:33:43,840 --> 00:33:45,760
DOCTOR: I've already done it.

506
00:33:46,280 --> 00:33:49,120
The words have gone. I got rid of them.

507
00:33:49,840 --> 00:33:52,640
The future I saw,
none of that will happen now.

508
00:33:52,840 --> 00:33:54,640
The message will never
contaminate my friends.

509
00:33:54,720 --> 00:33:57,120
No one will die.
No one is coming to save you.

510
00:33:59,360 --> 00:34:01,600
That's the thing about knowing
you're going to die,

511
00:34:02,400 --> 00:34:04,000
you've got nothing left to lose.

512
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:06,560
(YELLING)

513
00:34:06,680 --> 00:34:09,760
(BANGING RECEDES)

514
00:34:11,320 --> 00:34:12,760
No, no, no.
You've got to get out of here.

515
00:34:12,840 --> 00:34:14,440
The ghost locked me in. It's a trap.

516
00:34:18,480 --> 00:34:20,400
Come on! Faraday cage, now!

517
00:34:47,040 --> 00:34:49,320
(GROWLING)

518
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:04,320
The Time Lord.

519
00:35:05,440 --> 00:35:06,560
Night.

520
00:35:07,200 --> 00:35:09,120
(BEEPING)

521
00:35:12,080 --> 00:35:13,640
(QUICK BEEPING)

522
00:35:15,680 --> 00:35:17,400
(EXPLOSION)

523
00:35:28,640 --> 00:35:30,880
This is Security Protocol 712.

524
00:35:31,240 --> 00:35:33,320
The echelon circuit has been activated.

525
00:35:33,640 --> 00:35:36,440
Please stow any hand-luggage
and prepare for departure.

526
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:43,040
(ALL PANTING)

527
00:35:49,480 --> 00:35:50,720
Back. Get back.

528
00:35:52,040 --> 00:35:54,280
(BEEPING)

529
00:35:59,240 --> 00:36:01,320
(RUMBLING)

530
00:36:06,720 --> 00:36:08,640
(GROWLING)

531
00:36:12,120 --> 00:36:13,960
(ROARING)

532
00:36:21,440 --> 00:36:24,040
(WHIRRING)

533
00:36:27,760 --> 00:36:29,360
Don't kiss me. Morning breath.

534
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:31,280
(GASPS) Doctor?

535
00:36:32,760 --> 00:36:33,880
Follow me.

536
00:36:42,320 --> 00:36:43,320
(WHIRRING)

537
00:36:43,480 --> 00:36:45,600
-(ROARING)
-What's that noise?

538
00:36:45,960 --> 00:36:48,960
DOCTOR: It's the call of the
Fisher King. The call of their master.

539
00:36:49,080 --> 00:36:51,000
(ROARING)

540
00:36:55,840 --> 00:36:57,000
Where they going?

541
00:37:09,640 --> 00:37:12,160
(ROARING)

542
00:37:18,440 --> 00:37:19,880
(DOOR SLAMMING)

543
00:37:20,960 --> 00:37:22,360
(ELECTRICITY PULSING)

544
00:37:25,160 --> 00:37:26,200
So what was it?

545
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:28,120
-Your ghost?
-A hologram,

546
00:37:28,200 --> 00:37:31,080
like the one we made of you, to lure
the ghosts into the Faraday cage.

547
00:37:31,640 --> 00:37:33,880
With a soupcon
of artificial intelligence

548
00:37:33,960 --> 00:37:37,160
and a few pre-recorded
phrases from there. Eh!

549
00:37:38,640 --> 00:37:42,840
All beamed from the sonic glasses.

550
00:37:42,920 --> 00:37:44,760
As soon as you brought me
and the chamber on board

551
00:37:44,840 --> 00:37:47,480
it connected with the base's Wi-Fi.

552
00:37:48,760 --> 00:37:51,640
Bob's your uncle for the Ghost Doctor.

553
00:37:54,440 --> 00:37:55,840
CLARA: Why do they only
come out at night?

554
00:37:55,920 --> 00:37:58,720
Because they're electromagnetic
projections that were out of phase

555
00:37:58,800 --> 00:38:00,000
with the base's day-mode.

556
00:38:01,480 --> 00:38:02,480
Right!

557
00:38:04,200 --> 00:38:06,920
That's it. I've erased
the memory of the writing.

558
00:38:07,560 --> 00:38:09,880
Though, you might find you've lost
a couple of other memories, too.

559
00:38:09,960 --> 00:38:11,720
You know, like,
people you went to school with,

560
00:38:11,840 --> 00:38:14,200
or previous addresses,
or how to drink liquids.

561
00:38:14,280 --> 00:38:16,240
Uh, that's you two done.
Where's Bennett?

562
00:38:26,960 --> 00:38:28,360
What will happen to them?

563
00:38:28,440 --> 00:38:31,840
UNIT will cut out the Faraday cage
with them inside and take it away.

564
00:38:31,920 --> 00:38:33,680
Then the space hearse will be destroyed

565
00:38:33,760 --> 00:38:35,600
so the writing doesn't
infect anyone else.

566
00:38:36,680 --> 00:38:37,960
What do I do now?

567
00:38:39,120 --> 00:38:40,720
I don't understand.

568
00:38:40,960 --> 00:38:42,000
I do.

569
00:38:45,160 --> 00:38:47,200
You keep going. You have to.

570
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:51,560
Take it from me,
there is a whole world out there.

571
00:38:52,040 --> 00:38:55,040
A galaxy. A life.

572
00:38:56,120 --> 00:38:57,480
What would O'Donnell have wanted?

573
00:38:59,080 --> 00:39:02,040
I need to erase that message
from your mind, but it's fine.

574
00:39:02,280 --> 00:39:03,520
I'll do it later.

575
00:39:07,520 --> 00:39:09,120
Lunn, will you translate
something to Cass for me?

576
00:39:09,200 --> 00:39:10,440
Of course.

577
00:39:10,520 --> 00:39:12,920
Tell her that you're in love with her
and that you always have been.

578
00:39:13,000 --> 00:39:14,080
What?

579
00:39:14,160 --> 00:39:15,520
Tell her there's no point
in wasting time,

580
00:39:15,760 --> 00:39:18,160
'cause things happen
and then it's too late.

581
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:21,880
Tell her I wish someone
had given me that advice.

582
00:39:36,720 --> 00:39:38,080
Oh, God, no.

583
00:39:38,280 --> 00:39:41,000
I was just passing on what he said.
Please, don't...

584
00:39:50,440 --> 00:39:52,200
What will UNIT do with the ghosts?

585
00:39:52,520 --> 00:39:55,480
Drag the cage into space,
away from the Earth's magnetic field.

586
00:39:55,560 --> 00:39:58,280
With nothing to sustain them,
the ghosts will eventually fade away.

587
00:39:58,480 --> 00:40:00,240
Here's what I don't understand.

588
00:40:02,080 --> 00:40:03,720
You did change the future.

589
00:40:04,400 --> 00:40:06,120
You stopped the Fisher King
from returning.

590
00:40:06,520 --> 00:40:09,800
The Fisher King had been dead
for 150 years before we even got here,

591
00:40:10,840 --> 00:40:13,520
but once I went back,
I became part of events.

592
00:40:15,520 --> 00:40:16,680
But here's the thing,

593
00:40:17,080 --> 00:40:19,240
the messages my ghost gave,
they weren't for you.

594
00:40:20,320 --> 00:40:21,320
They were for me.

595
00:40:21,600 --> 00:40:25,360
That list.
Everyone after you was random,

596
00:40:25,480 --> 00:40:26,760
but you being the next name,

597
00:40:26,840 --> 00:40:29,440
that's what made me confront
the Fisher King.

598
00:40:29,520 --> 00:40:31,160
And saying the chamber will open?

599
00:40:31,240 --> 00:40:34,720
That was me telling me to get inside
and when to set it for.

600
00:40:36,560 --> 00:40:37,680
Smart.

601
00:40:37,800 --> 00:40:39,000
(BOTH LAUGH)

602
00:40:39,960 --> 00:40:41,960
Except that's not why I said them.

603
00:40:42,880 --> 00:40:43,960
CLARA: How do you mean?

604
00:40:45,360 --> 00:40:47,320
I programmed my ghost to say them

605
00:40:47,400 --> 00:40:49,120
because that's what my ghost had said.

606
00:40:49,480 --> 00:40:52,280
And the only reason that I created
my ghost hologram in the first place,

607
00:40:52,520 --> 00:40:53,880
was because I saw it here.

608
00:40:53,960 --> 00:40:57,120
I was reverse engineering the narrative.

609
00:40:57,480 --> 00:40:59,240
Okay. That's still pretty smart.

610
00:40:59,560 --> 00:41:02,000
You do not understand.

611
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:06,120
When did I first
have those ideas, Clara?

612
00:41:07,280 --> 00:41:09,200
Well, it must have been...

613
00:41:13,320 --> 00:41:15,640
-Wow!
-Exactly!

614
00:41:16,440 --> 00:41:18,600
Who composed Beethoven's Fifth?

615
00:41:27,160 --> 00:41:29,080
-(EXPLOSION)
-CLARA: Doctor, help me!

616
00:41:29,160 --> 00:41:30,880
DOCTOR: Yes, you're
the very next thing on the list.

617
00:41:31,560 --> 00:41:32,840
VIKING: We are Vikings!

618
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:34,680
(SHOUTING)

619
00:41:34,960 --> 00:41:36,800
You fight or you die.

620
00:41:36,880 --> 00:41:38,080
They are called the Mire.

621
00:41:38,160 --> 00:41:40,200
-You will beg for mercy.
-Ha, ha, ha!

622
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:41,760
CLARA: The deadliest
warrior race in the galaxy?

623
00:41:41,840 --> 00:41:42,880
One of them, yes. Why?

624
00:41:42,960 --> 00:41:44,560
CLARA: I think this village
Just declared war on them.

625
00:41:44,640 --> 00:41:46,880
DOCTOR: There's gonna be a war.
I hear some news.

626
00:41:46,960 --> 00:41:48,400
We are gonna win the hell out of it.

627
00:41:48,520 --> 00:41:49,960
-GIRL: Why are you here?
-I'm the Doctor,

628
00:41:50,040 --> 00:41:52,040
-and I save people.
-(SCREAMING)

